1
00:00:23,801 --> 00:00:25,386
Quiet on the set.

2
00:00:27,054 --> 00:00:29,098
Scene one, take ten.
Marker.

3
00:00:36,397 --> 00:00:38,941
And action!

4
00:00:41,194 --> 00:00:43,154
Joel Levison's office.

5
00:00:43,237 --> 00:00:46,783
l'm sorry, he's not in yet.
May l take a message?

6
00:00:46,866 --> 00:00:49,660
- Mr. Levy, l'll tell him you called.
- Never say that.

7
00:00:49,744 --> 00:00:53,080
He's either in conference, in a meeting.
He's always in.

8
00:00:53,164 --> 00:00:55,333
- Who was that?
- Larry Levy.

9
00:00:56,709 --> 00:00:59,212
Was there anything in the trades
this morning?

10
00:00:59,295 --> 00:01:02,840
- l don't know. The mail's late.
- Go get them. Now!

11
00:01:02,924 --> 00:01:06,135
l want them back here
before he arrives.

12
00:01:21,067 --> 00:01:25,113
Griffin, hi. Adam Simon.

13
00:01:25,196 --> 00:01:27,532
We weren't supposed to meet
until next week, but--

14
00:01:27,615 --> 00:01:31,661
- l didn't know we were.
- l wanted to plant a seed in your head.

15
00:01:31,744 --> 00:01:34,247
- l'm booked up.
- Picture this.

16
00:01:34,330 --> 00:01:36,999
lt's a planet in the far future
with two suns.

17
00:01:37,041 --> 00:01:39,293
- Who plays the sons?
- No, suns. Large solar disks.

18
00:01:39,377 --> 00:01:41,295
Run this idea by Bonnie Sherow.

19
00:01:41,379 --> 00:01:44,757
The pictures they make these days
are all MTV. Cut, cut, cut.

20
00:01:44,841 --> 00:01:48,302
The opening shot of Touch of Evil
was six and a half minutes long.

21
00:01:48,386 --> 00:01:50,847
- Six and a half minutes?
- Three or four, anyway.

22
00:01:50,930 --> 00:01:54,142
He set up the whole picture
with that one tracking shot.

23
00:01:54,225 --> 00:01:56,602
My father was key grip on that shoot.

24
00:01:56,686 --> 00:02:00,898
What about Absolute Beginners?
That was an extraordinary shot.

25
00:02:00,940 --> 00:02:04,235
- Never heard of it.
- lt's an English film.

26
00:02:08,614 --> 00:02:11,701
- A Peligrino, please.
- l've got Calistoga.

27
00:02:11,784 --> 00:02:13,828
- Buck, how are you?
- Good. How you doin'?

28
00:02:13,911 --> 00:02:18,249
- Good. What have you got for me?
- Okay, here it is.

29
00:02:18,332 --> 00:02:21,169
- The Graduate, Part ll.
- Oh, good.

30
00:02:21,252 --> 00:02:24,255
Listen, the three principals
are still with us.

31
00:02:24,338 --> 00:02:29,802
Dustin Hoffman, Anne Bancroft,
Katharine Ross, 25 years later.

32
00:02:29,886 --> 00:02:34,849
And so are the characters,
Ben, Elaine and Mrs. Robinson.

33
00:02:34,932 --> 00:02:36,851
Ben and Elaine are married, still.

34
00:02:36,934 --> 00:02:41,606
They live in a big, spooky house
up in northern California somewhere.

35
00:02:41,689 --> 00:02:44,776
And Mrs. Robinson
lives with them...

36
00:02:44,859 --> 00:02:49,572
her aging mother
who's had a stroke...

37
00:02:49,614 --> 00:02:51,574
so she can't talk.

38
00:02:51,616 --> 00:02:55,203
- Will it be funny?
- lt'll be funny. Dark, weird and funny.

39
00:02:55,286 --> 00:02:58,623
And with a stroke.
Maybe it's not a stroke.

40
00:02:58,706 --> 00:03:01,375
l don't know what it is.
lt's a malady of some sort.

41
00:03:01,459 --> 00:03:05,046
She's up in the bedroom listening
to everything that happens.

42
00:03:05,129 --> 00:03:08,049
They've got a daughter
who's just graduated from college.

43
00:03:08,132 --> 00:03:12,470
Twenty-two, twenty-three-year-old,
like a Julia Roberts.

44
00:03:12,512 --> 00:03:14,555
Excuse me.
What should l do with these scripts?

45
00:03:14,639 --> 00:03:19,977
They go to Bonnie. And find out from
security how Adam Simon got on the lot.

46
00:03:20,019 --> 00:03:23,981
- l want to know.
- Adam Simon? Okay.

47
00:03:24,065 --> 00:03:27,151
Julia Roberts comes home,
their daughter, the graduate.

48
00:03:27,235 --> 00:03:29,070
The new graduate.

49
00:03:29,153 --> 00:03:31,781
Griffin loved it.
He wanted me to run it by you.

50
00:03:31,864 --> 00:03:37,203
- lt's a band of human survivors.
- Write this down for me.

51
00:03:37,286 --> 00:03:40,373
l can't process this.
Write it down for me.

52
00:03:40,456 --> 00:03:43,584
lt's not about words.
You have to visualize.

53
00:03:46,963 --> 00:03:51,050
Jimmy, are you okay?
What happened?

54
00:03:52,385 --> 00:03:55,930
- Are you all right?
- My name's Jimmy Chase.

55
00:03:57,974 --> 00:04:01,644
He came out of nowhere, ran right
in front of the cart. l never saw him.

56
00:04:06,607 --> 00:04:08,901
- That's Adam Simon.
- How you doin', kid?

57
00:04:18,327 --> 00:04:21,706
Rebecca DeMornay.
Actually, you're better looking.

58
00:04:21,747 --> 00:04:24,834
- No, l'm not Rebecca DeMornay.
- You're a dead ringer.

59
00:04:24,876 --> 00:04:26,586
Thank you very much.

60
00:04:26,669 --> 00:04:29,422
Do you know where
Joel Levison's office is?

61
00:04:29,505 --> 00:04:32,341
The head of the studio?

62
00:04:32,383 --> 00:04:34,343
lt's moving.
lt'll rip your heart out.

63
00:04:34,385 --> 00:04:39,265
This is the area where we make decisions
to give a green light to a picture.

64
00:04:39,348 --> 00:04:43,853
We're going to go 17 stories high.
We'll continue to use all Sony products.

65
00:04:43,895 --> 00:04:46,939
Domo arigato to the Sony products.

66
00:04:47,023 --> 00:04:51,527
lf you need someone to eat sashimi
with you, give me a ring.

67
00:04:57,784 --> 00:05:00,077
The traffic from Malibu
was impossible.

68
00:05:00,161 --> 00:05:03,748
- Good morning, Joel.
- Sandy, park the car, please.

69
00:05:03,831 --> 00:05:05,833
Good morning Marty, Annie.

70
00:05:07,960 --> 00:05:12,632
- What are the Japs doing here?
- What's this talk about heads rolling?

71
00:05:12,715 --> 00:05:15,843
The bank's putting screws to us.
Goldman's son is coming out from Boston.

72
00:05:15,927 --> 00:05:17,345
l don't like it.

73
00:05:17,428 --> 00:05:20,890
Reggie Goldman's a pipsqueak.
You can't be serious.

74
00:05:20,932 --> 00:05:25,186
Some changes are going on here.
That's always the way.

75
00:05:25,269 --> 00:05:28,106
lt happened at Paramount
three years ago.

76
00:05:28,147 --> 00:05:30,233
Columbia's going through it now.

77
00:05:30,316 --> 00:05:32,610
l hear we're looking
to replace Griffin.

78
00:05:32,652 --> 00:05:34,987
Griffin? l don't believe it.
With whom?

79
00:05:35,071 --> 00:05:38,449
Burke or Patrick.
Maybe Larry Levy.

80
00:05:38,533 --> 00:05:42,245
l want to know why
the security is lax.

81
00:05:42,286 --> 00:05:45,289
l'll talk to you later.
l'm in the middle of a pitch.

82
00:05:45,373 --> 00:05:47,542
Listen, go ahead.

83
00:05:47,625 --> 00:05:52,922
- lt's a TV star who goes on a safari.
- A TV star in a motion picture?

84
00:05:52,964 --> 00:05:57,927
- A TV star played by a movie star.
- A movie star playing a TV star.

85
00:05:57,969 --> 00:06:02,306
- Michelle, Bette, Lily.
- Dolly Parton would be good.

86
00:06:02,390 --> 00:06:07,645
- l like Goldie.
- Great, because we have a relationship.

87
00:06:07,728 --> 00:06:10,189
Goldie goes to Africa.

88
00:06:10,273 --> 00:06:15,945
- She's found by this tribe.
- Of small people.

89
00:06:16,028 --> 00:06:18,906
She's found and they worship her.

90
00:06:18,990 --> 00:06:23,786
lt's like The Gods Must Be Crazy
except the coke bottle is an actress.

91
00:06:23,828 --> 00:06:26,456
Right. lt's Out of Africa
meets Pretty Woman.

92
00:06:26,539 --> 00:06:30,126
She has to decide whether to stay
with the TV show...

93
00:06:30,168 --> 00:06:32,670
or save the tribe.

94
00:06:32,753 --> 00:06:35,715
- Where's Griffin Mill's office?
- Right here.

95
00:06:35,798 --> 00:06:38,718
- You're Martin Scorsese!
- No, but l know Harvey Keitel.

96
00:06:38,801 --> 00:06:42,305
l know you do.
l loved Cape Fear.

97
00:06:42,346 --> 00:06:45,057
My old man worked for Hitchcock.

98
00:06:45,141 --> 00:06:47,393
Rope. lt was a masterpiece.

99
00:06:47,477 --> 00:06:50,271
The story wasn't any good.
He shot the whole thing without cuts.

100
00:06:50,354 --> 00:06:52,231
l hate all this 'Cut, cut, cut!'

101
00:06:52,315 --> 00:06:57,820
What about Bertolucci, the great shot
with Winger in Sheltering Sky?

102
00:06:57,862 --> 00:06:59,947
l didn't see it.

103
00:07:03,326 --> 00:07:07,330
- l've been here since 8:00.
- l took a chance getting you this job.

104
00:07:07,413 --> 00:07:11,375
- Who were you with?
- l was with Alan Rudolph.

105
00:07:11,459 --> 00:07:16,380
- What were you doing with him?
- He asked me to have coffee.

106
00:07:16,422 --> 00:07:19,008
You're my assistant.
You don't get involved with writers.

107
00:07:19,050 --> 00:07:21,969
l wasn't getting involved. l was
listening to this amazing idea he had.

108
00:07:22,053 --> 00:07:24,555
That's interesting.
What's your pitch?

109
00:07:24,639 --> 00:07:28,059
- Does political scare you?
- Political doesn't scare me.

110
00:07:28,142 --> 00:07:30,853
Radical political scares me.
Political political scares me.

111
00:07:30,895 --> 00:07:34,440
This is politely politically radical,
but it's funny.

112
00:07:34,524 --> 00:07:38,820
- lt's a funny political thing.
- And it's a thriller, too, all at once.

113
00:07:38,903 --> 00:07:43,032
-What's the story?
-l want Bruce Willis. l can talk to him.

114
00:07:43,116 --> 00:07:46,577
lt's a story about a bad-guy senator.

115
00:07:46,661 --> 00:07:51,124
He's traveling around the country
on the country's dime, like Sununu did.

116
00:07:51,207 --> 00:07:53,668
lt's a cynical, political
thriller comedy.

117
00:07:53,751 --> 00:07:59,006
But it's got heart in the right spot.
Anyway, he has an accident.

118
00:07:59,090 --> 00:08:03,886
And he becomes clairvoyant,
like a psychic.

119
00:08:03,928 --> 00:08:07,056
So it's a psychic, political,
thriller comedy with a heart.

120
00:08:07,140 --> 00:08:11,477
With a heart, not unlike Ghost
meets Manchurian Candidate.

121
00:08:11,561 --> 00:08:15,064
- Go on, l'm listening.
- He starts reading people's minds.

122
00:08:15,148 --> 00:08:19,735
And when he gets to the President's mind
it's completely blank.

123
00:08:19,819 --> 00:08:22,071
- Can l get you anything?
- l'd like a beer, please.

124
00:08:22,113 --> 00:08:25,241
- We don't have beer.
- Red wine, please.

125
00:08:26,951 --> 00:08:31,998
Someone gets killed at the end.
They always do in political thrillers.

126
00:08:32,123 --> 00:08:36,377
- Griffin Mill's office.
- Can you put him on?

127
00:08:36,419 --> 00:08:40,173
- May l ask who's calling?
- l'd like to speak to Griffin Mill.

128
00:08:40,256 --> 00:08:44,427
He's in a meeting right now. l can take
your name and have him get back to you.

129
00:08:44,510 --> 00:08:47,889
- Excuse me?
- He'll get back to me?

130
00:08:47,930 --> 00:08:51,392
- Do you know how often l've heard this?
- Who is this?

131
00:08:51,434 --> 00:08:54,562
- lf he doesn't get back to me--
- Who was that?

132
00:08:54,645 --> 00:08:57,648
- l don't know. He didn't say.
- What do you mean?

133
00:08:57,732 --> 00:09:03,029
l don't know how you'll cast it. The
lead is a 50-year-old circus performer.

134
00:09:03,112 --> 00:09:05,448
Let me read the coverage.

135
00:09:05,531 --> 00:09:07,617
Are we still having lunch
with Aaron Camp?

136
00:09:07,700 --> 00:09:10,787
- What time?
- l made it for 1:00.

137
00:09:10,870 --> 00:09:13,289
- Bad day?
- He's having writer's block.

138
00:09:15,374 --> 00:09:19,837
You have a meeting with Hutter and
Frank South this afternoon at 3:00.

139
00:09:19,921 --> 00:09:23,591
l'll be here. Put this morning's
meetings on the computer. Thanks.

140
00:09:24,759 --> 00:09:27,804
- Are you going now?
- l'm going to see Levison.

141
00:09:27,887 --> 00:09:30,807
Order me a Caesar salad
and a Crystal Geyser.

142
00:09:38,856 --> 00:09:42,235
About 5:00? Thanks, Sandy.

143
00:09:42,318 --> 00:09:44,612
Hi, Sandy.

144
00:09:44,654 --> 00:09:47,782
You can't go in there!
He's in a meeting.

145
00:09:48,950 --> 00:09:51,786
lt's all right, Celia.

146
00:09:51,869 --> 00:09:55,498
l don't think you've met Reg Goldman.
You know his father Harvey.

147
00:09:55,581 --> 00:09:59,293
Yes, of course. Hi, Reg.
From the bank in Boston.

148
00:09:59,377 --> 00:10:04,465
- Reg is out here for a few weeks.
- Great. Business or pleasure?

149
00:10:04,507 --> 00:10:07,135
A little of both, l hope.

150
00:10:07,176 --> 00:10:08,970
Reg is thinking of producing.

151
00:10:09,053 --> 00:10:11,055
Really?

152
00:10:11,139 --> 00:10:13,432
Yeah. Beats work,
doesn't it, Griffin?

153
00:10:13,516 --> 00:10:15,852
l'd like to play some tennis.
Do you play tennis?

154
00:10:15,935 --> 00:10:18,312
Tennis? No.

155
00:10:18,354 --> 00:10:21,023
- l'm too busy.
- l was asking Walter.

156
00:10:21,107 --> 00:10:23,443
Do you know Meg Ryan?

157
00:10:23,526 --> 00:10:25,486
ls she seeing somebody?

158
00:10:26,779 --> 00:10:29,157
Yeah, Reg. She's married.

159
00:10:30,366 --> 00:10:31,784
Shit.

160
00:10:31,868 --> 00:10:34,495
What about Winona Ryder?

161
00:10:34,579 --> 00:10:39,459
You know, actually,
Walter is the guy to talk to.

162
00:10:39,542 --> 00:10:41,878
Walter's got everybody's number.

163
00:10:41,961 --> 00:10:46,048
- Was there anything?
- No. You're real busy.

164
00:10:46,132 --> 00:10:49,510
l want that number, goddamn it.
l want that number.

165
00:10:49,552 --> 00:10:53,181
Oh, boy. What about this one?
Has she done anything?

166
00:10:54,307 --> 00:10:55,725
Celia.

167
00:10:57,143 --> 00:11:00,146
Griffin, don't ask.

168
00:11:00,229 --> 00:11:04,650
Don't ask, you don't know?
Or don't ask, l don't want to know?

169
00:11:04,734 --> 00:11:07,028
Just don't ask.

170
00:11:08,154 --> 00:11:12,909
lf it's Reggie Goldman
you're concerned about, forget it.

171
00:11:12,992 --> 00:11:15,495
But be nice to him. He represents
a lot of money to this company.

172
00:11:15,578 --> 00:11:18,623
lt's not Reggie Goldman
l'm worried about.

173
00:11:18,706 --> 00:11:21,250
- lt's Larry Levy.
- Larry Levy?

174
00:11:22,251 --> 00:11:24,670
Larry Levy's at Fox, isn't he?

175
00:11:26,547 --> 00:11:28,758
Come on, Celia.

176
00:11:28,841 --> 00:11:31,969
There's a call for Celia
on line one.

177
00:11:32,053 --> 00:11:35,473
- Should l be looking for a job?
- Celia, are you there?

178
00:11:35,556 --> 00:11:39,894
Joel Levison's office.
Oh, Brad. Yeah.

179
00:11:39,936 --> 00:11:41,479
What?

180
00:11:41,562 --> 00:11:46,067
No, we couldn't sign Angelica Huston
for that. She's booked for two years.

181
00:11:46,150 --> 00:11:50,738
Like a ghost story,
but it's not like Ghost.

182
00:11:54,242 --> 00:11:56,410
lt's a supernatural thing.

183
00:11:58,913 --> 00:12:01,624
Joel, Griffin Mill.
A friend of Jennifer's.

184
00:12:01,707 --> 00:12:04,836
No. You're Griffin Mill?
Really?

185
00:12:04,919 --> 00:12:06,838
Good to see you.
l'm a big fan of yours.

186
00:12:06,921 --> 00:12:09,590
- l have that tie.
- You do?

187
00:12:16,013 --> 00:12:18,141
Did you order for me?

188
00:12:20,601 --> 00:12:24,313
Hi. Lunching with the enemy.

189
00:12:24,397 --> 00:12:26,357
Oh, come on.

190
00:12:26,441 --> 00:12:29,569
So what's this we hear
about Larry Levy?

191
00:12:29,652 --> 00:12:33,281
Larry Levy? lf he had half a brain,
he'd be dangerous.

192
00:12:35,241 --> 00:12:37,618
Aaron says he's coming
to the studio.

193
00:12:37,660 --> 00:12:42,331
Aaron says? Why would you believe
anything he says?

194
00:12:42,415 --> 00:12:45,126
He said it with authority.

195
00:12:45,209 --> 00:12:49,964
He's over there with Angelica Huston
and John Cusack.

196
00:12:50,047 --> 00:12:53,134
He's in over his head.
He's gonna drown over there.

197
00:12:54,177 --> 00:12:56,721
He's the golden boy at Fox these days.

198
00:12:56,804 --> 00:12:59,640
Did you see that thing on him
in Variety last week?

199
00:12:59,724 --> 00:13:01,267
Two pages.

200
00:13:01,350 --> 00:13:05,271
Angelica, Griffin Mill.
Good to see you. You're looking great.

201
00:13:05,354 --> 00:13:08,316
Johnny, Griffin Mill.
A big fan of yours.

202
00:13:08,357 --> 00:13:11,444
- You gonna be in Telluride this year?
- Probably in Park City.

203
00:13:11,527 --> 00:13:13,696
Great. We'll see you there.

204
00:13:15,364 --> 00:13:20,787
- What's happening with Glass Box?
- Let's not talk about Hollywood.

205
00:13:20,870 --> 00:13:23,414
We're educated people.

206
00:13:28,544 --> 00:13:30,671
l'll call you later.

207
00:14:03,037 --> 00:14:05,498
- Talk to somebody about this.
- What?

208
00:14:05,581 --> 00:14:08,376
- You've gotten 5 postcards in 2 weeks.
- Seven, actually.

209
00:14:08,459 --> 00:14:11,045
Why don't you talk to Studio Security?

210
00:14:11,129 --> 00:14:13,256
l should call Walter Stuckel
and say what?

211
00:14:13,339 --> 00:14:18,052
'Someone's sending me poison letters
and l would like for you to make me...

212
00:14:18,094 --> 00:14:21,722
the object of more ridicule now that
things are really shaky for me here.(

213
00:14:21,806 --> 00:14:23,266
l don't think so.

214
00:14:23,307 --> 00:14:25,351
l think they're coming from a writer.

215
00:14:25,435 --> 00:14:27,395
- Which one?
- Take your pick.

216
00:14:29,939 --> 00:14:32,275
- ls there anything else?
- Yes, your attorney phoned.

217
00:14:32,358 --> 00:14:35,194
He wants you to attend a party
at his house tonight.

218
00:14:35,278 --> 00:14:38,239
- Tell him l'm at a screening.
- Not that attorney. lt's Dick Mellen.

219
00:14:38,281 --> 00:14:39,740
What time?

220
00:14:39,782 --> 00:14:42,785
Cocktails at 7:30, dinner at 8:00.
Bring a date.

221
00:14:42,827 --> 00:14:45,079
And Bonnie Sherow is here to see you.

222
00:14:45,163 --> 00:14:48,124
Send her in.
Oh, here she is.

223
00:14:48,166 --> 00:14:51,252
Can we go to the Springs this weekend?

224
00:14:51,335 --> 00:14:55,923
l want to have a massage,
a long soak in a hot tub...

225
00:14:55,965 --> 00:14:59,218
and have Margaritas administered
intravenously.

226
00:14:59,302 --> 00:15:01,512
l have a party at Dick Mellen's.
You want to come?

227
00:15:01,596 --> 00:15:04,140
God, movie stars and power players.

228
00:15:04,223 --> 00:15:07,143
