695
00:49:11,020 --> 00:49:14,357
Garbage can lids are lifted
as derelicts in the street...

696
00:49:14,398 --> 00:49:16,859
hunt for food.

697
00:49:16,943 --> 00:49:19,362
Buzzing, as a cheap alarm clock
goes off.

698
00:49:19,445 --> 00:49:23,157
lnterior. Flophouse room.
Early morning.

699
00:49:23,199 --> 00:49:26,327
A tracking shot moves
through the grimy room.

700
00:49:26,410 --> 00:49:29,997
Light streams in through holes
in yellowing window shades.

701
00:49:30,081 --> 00:49:32,750
Moths dance
in the beams of light.

702
00:49:32,834 --> 00:49:36,170
Track down along the floor.
The frayed rug.

703
00:49:36,212 --> 00:49:39,173
Stop on an old shoe.

704
00:49:39,215 --> 00:49:40,925
lt's empty.(

705
00:49:45,179 --> 00:49:47,265
That's as far as he got.

706
00:49:48,641 --> 00:49:51,102
That's the last thing he wrote.

707
00:49:51,978 --> 00:49:54,188
So long, Dave.

708
00:49:54,230 --> 00:49:56,441
Fade out.

709
00:49:56,524 --> 00:49:57,942
Thank you.

710
00:50:14,250 --> 00:50:16,752
Who are you?
You're not a writer.

711
00:50:18,504 --> 00:50:20,840
No, l'm Griffin Mill.

712
00:50:20,923 --> 00:50:22,842
We spoke the night David--

713
00:50:22,925 --> 00:50:25,761
Blue sea, white sea.
Yes.

714
00:50:25,803 --> 00:50:28,097
- lt turned out you were right.
- What?

715
00:50:28,181 --> 00:50:30,600
lt was a red sea.

716
00:50:30,683 --> 00:50:32,435
Oh, yeah.

717
00:50:34,896 --> 00:50:38,065
You're the only person l know here.

718
00:50:38,107 --> 00:50:40,985
l'm really sorry about David.

719
00:50:41,068 --> 00:50:44,155
He was a talent.

720
00:50:45,323 --> 00:50:47,533
You really think so?

721
00:50:47,617 --> 00:50:50,870
l always suspected he was...

722
00:50:50,953 --> 00:50:53,581
uniquely untalented.

723
00:50:55,124 --> 00:50:58,294
lt's nice of you to say that. lt was
nice of you to come. You didn't have to.

724
00:50:58,377 --> 00:50:59,796
l did.

725
00:50:59,879 --> 00:51:04,425
You know, l was probably the last person
to see him alive.

726
00:51:04,467 --> 00:51:06,803
The police told me.

727
00:51:06,844 --> 00:51:08,971
Not quite the last, surely.

728
00:51:12,141 --> 00:51:15,353
l'm sure this is a terrible time
for you.

729
00:51:15,436 --> 00:51:17,772
ls there anything you need?

730
00:51:17,814 --> 00:51:22,527
No, really.
l don't feel bad.

731
00:51:22,610 --> 00:51:25,488
lt's like when my parents died.

732
00:51:25,530 --> 00:51:29,075
l didn't feel anything at all.
They were just gone.

733
00:51:30,785 --> 00:51:33,996
l'm sure it hasn't sunk in yet.

734
00:51:34,080 --> 00:51:35,832
That was years ago.

735
00:51:35,873 --> 00:51:38,668
No, l meant David.

736
00:51:38,709 --> 00:51:40,586
Oh, God.

737
00:51:40,670 --> 00:51:43,673
These people.
l don't like it here.

738
00:51:43,756 --> 00:51:47,343
They're all expecting me
to grieve and mourn.

739
00:51:47,426 --> 00:51:49,720
l can't talk to them.

740
00:51:51,472 --> 00:51:56,602
David's gone and
l'm somewhere else already.

741
00:51:56,686 --> 00:51:59,522
- Will you take me home?
- What?

742
00:51:59,564 --> 00:52:02,316
Will you take me home?

743
00:52:02,358 --> 00:52:05,153
Sure. l'm right here.

744
00:52:42,148 --> 00:52:44,776
These are very interesting.
l like them.

745
00:52:44,859 --> 00:52:48,488
- Would you like a drink?
- No, thanks.

746
00:52:48,571 --> 00:52:52,492
Where do you show?
What gallery? Who's your dealer?

747
00:52:52,575 --> 00:52:54,994
l don't have a dealer.

748
00:52:55,077 --> 00:52:58,039
l couldn't sell these.
They're never finished. Biccy?

749
00:52:59,624 --> 00:53:02,585
No, thanks.
They're never finished?

750
00:53:02,668 --> 00:53:07,131
No, they're just what l do
for myself.

751
00:53:07,173 --> 00:53:09,717
What l feel.

752
00:53:09,801 --> 00:53:12,470
You ask lots of questions, Mr. Mill.

753
00:53:12,553 --> 00:53:16,307
Just like the police.
That's all they did, ask questions.

754
00:53:18,017 --> 00:53:19,936
They asked me a lot about you.

755
00:53:20,019 --> 00:53:21,729
Did they?

756
00:53:21,813 --> 00:53:23,731
How long we'd known each other.

757
00:53:23,815 --> 00:53:25,817
lf you'd ever been
to the house before.

758
00:53:25,900 --> 00:53:30,738
- They have to ask those questions.
- l don't see why.

759
00:53:30,822 --> 00:53:33,074
Because that's what police do.

760
00:53:34,117 --> 00:53:37,286
- Can l ask you a question?
- Sure.

761
00:53:37,370 --> 00:53:40,123
Why was it so important
to see David that night?

762
00:53:40,206 --> 00:53:42,291
What was so urgent?

763
00:53:43,960 --> 00:53:46,838
He pitched me a story
a few months ago.

764
00:53:46,921 --> 00:53:49,215
- The Japan story?
- Yes, the Japan story.

765
00:53:49,298 --> 00:53:52,844
l liked it but it needed work,
especially the ending.

766
00:53:52,927 --> 00:53:55,721
l was sitting in my office...

767
00:53:55,805 --> 00:53:58,766
and it suddenly occurred to me
how to make the ending work.

768
00:53:58,850 --> 00:54:00,977
So what was it?

769
00:54:01,060 --> 00:54:02,478
What?

770
00:54:02,562 --> 00:54:05,523
Your idea for the ending.

771
00:54:05,606 --> 00:54:07,608
Up.

772
00:54:07,692 --> 00:54:09,861
Up? What does that mean?

773
00:54:09,944 --> 00:54:12,697
As opposed to down. Moods.

774
00:54:12,780 --> 00:54:15,950
You know, happy as opposed to sad.
Hopeful as opposed to depressing.

775
00:54:16,033 --> 00:54:19,704
- What did you think of his ending?
- l never read it.

776
00:54:21,622 --> 00:54:24,250
- You never read it?
- Nope.

777
00:54:24,333 --> 00:54:26,752
l don't like reading.

778
00:54:26,836 --> 00:54:32,008
- Do you like books?
- l like words and letters.

779
00:54:32,091 --> 00:54:34,343
But l'm not crazy
about complete sentences.

780
00:54:36,095 --> 00:54:38,598
What did he think?

781
00:54:38,681 --> 00:54:42,435
He walked out on me.
l don't think David liked me.

782
00:54:42,518 --> 00:54:46,439
l think he just didn't like
happy endings.

783
00:54:50,193 --> 00:54:52,361
Put your face here.

784
00:54:53,905 --> 00:54:55,323
Great.

785
00:54:57,492 --> 00:55:00,077
What are you doing?
You aren't going to paint me, are you?

786
00:55:00,161 --> 00:55:03,414
l might put you
in one of my paintings.

787
00:55:03,456 --> 00:55:07,126
There's one l want to do
of an lcelandic hero.

788
00:55:07,210 --> 00:55:10,213
He's a thief
and he's made of fire.

789
00:55:10,296 --> 00:55:12,840
- You might not like that.
- Why not?

790
00:55:12,924 --> 00:55:15,635
Because you're in the movies...

791
00:55:15,718 --> 00:55:19,639
and in movies you can't have thieves
as heroes, can you?

792
00:55:19,722 --> 00:55:23,309
l don't know about that. We have a long
tradition of gangsters in movies.

793
00:55:23,392 --> 00:55:27,105
Yes, but they always have to suffer
for their crimes, don't they?

794
00:55:28,689 --> 00:55:30,858
We should pay for our crimes,
shouldn't we?

795
00:55:30,942 --> 00:55:35,279
l think knowing you've committed a crime
is suffering enough.

796
00:55:35,321 --> 00:55:37,323
lf you don't suffer...

797
00:55:37,406 --> 00:55:41,119
maybe it wasn't a crime after all.

798
00:55:41,160 --> 00:55:43,704
Anyway, what difference does it make?

799
00:55:43,788 --> 00:55:47,041
lt has nothing to do
with how things really are.

800
00:55:51,379 --> 00:55:54,048
Do you really believe that?

801
00:55:54,132 --> 00:55:57,510
l don't know what l believe, Mr. Mill.

802
00:55:57,593 --> 00:56:00,388
lt's just what l feel.

803
00:56:02,056 --> 00:56:05,852
You know what you are,
June whatever-your-name-is?

804
00:56:05,935 --> 00:56:07,603
A pragmatic anarchist.

805
00:56:09,063 --> 00:56:11,023
ls that what l am?

806
00:56:11,065 --> 00:56:13,192
l never was sure.

807
00:56:17,697 --> 00:56:20,116
Can l just pick this up?

808
00:56:21,367 --> 00:56:24,162
- Oh, it's heavy.
- Thirty-seven ounces.

809
00:56:24,203 --> 00:56:26,706
Really? Look.

810
00:56:26,747 --> 00:56:30,960
l want to thank my mother, her mother
and her father's mother who--

811
00:56:32,962 --> 00:56:34,380
Hello.

812
00:56:35,840 --> 00:56:39,343
- Meet Detective Susan Avery.
- How do you do? My partner.

813
00:56:39,427 --> 00:56:42,513
- Willa Broom.
- My pleasure. Let's go in here.

814
00:56:42,597 --> 00:56:45,433
This is the first real movie studio
Detective Avery's been to.

815
00:56:45,516 --> 00:56:48,519
- Really?
- Aside from the Universal Tour.

816
00:56:48,603 --> 00:56:51,189
l always take my family there
when they come.

817
00:56:51,272 --> 00:56:54,817
l've been there so often,
l feel like l'm ready to direct.

818
00:56:54,901 --> 00:56:59,405
You'd probably do better
than the film grads these days.

819
00:56:59,489 --> 00:57:02,158
l'm sorry l didn't call you
when l heard Kahane was dead.

820
00:57:02,241 --> 00:57:03,910
- Heard or read?
- Read.

821
00:57:03,951 --> 00:57:07,413
- Why didn't you?
- Walter asked me the same question.

822
00:57:07,497 --> 00:57:11,542
l wish l had a better answer. All
l can say is l didn't think about it.

823
00:57:14,045 --> 00:57:16,130
How did you know where
he was gonna be?

824
00:57:16,214 --> 00:57:19,550
- His wife told me--
- Girlfriend.

825
00:57:20,551 --> 00:57:21,969
Girlfriend.

826
00:57:22,053 --> 00:57:24,263
Girlfriend.
l didn't know either of them.

827
00:57:24,305 --> 00:57:26,682
l was restless,
thought l'd see the movie.

828
00:57:26,766 --> 00:57:30,144
lf he was there, l'd talk to him
about a job l thought he was good for.

829
00:57:30,228 --> 00:57:32,396
You got to the theater,
saw him and?

830
00:57:32,438 --> 00:57:35,108
We had a drink at a Japanese place.

831
00:57:35,191 --> 00:57:39,070
lt was a wild, incredible scene.
lt was like Tokyo.

832
00:57:39,153 --> 00:57:41,989
He left before you.
Why didn't you leave together?

833
00:57:42,073 --> 00:57:44,700
lt was an incredible scene.
l was having a great time.

834
00:57:44,784 --> 00:57:46,619
Why didn't you stay longer?

835
00:57:46,702 --> 00:57:50,915
People stopped singing. Then it was just
a bar and l don't drink.

836
00:57:50,998 --> 00:57:53,918
- You drank with him.
- When in Rome--

837
00:57:54,001 --> 00:57:57,964
Did you know him socially?
Been to his house?

838
00:57:58,047 --> 00:58:00,091
Know anything about him personally?

839
00:58:02,009 --> 00:58:04,929
We'll let you get back to work now.

840
00:58:07,473 --> 00:58:09,475
What's bothering you?

841
00:58:09,559 --> 00:58:12,437
Well, l just have to ask.

842
00:58:12,478 --> 00:58:16,315
Did you see him in the parking lot
after you left?

843
00:58:16,399 --> 00:58:19,986
No, l parked on the street.
l drive a Range Rover...

844
00:58:20,069 --> 00:58:22,488
so l feel safer
when it's visible.

845
00:58:22,572 --> 00:58:25,199
Who's gonna smash a window
if it's on the street?

846
00:58:25,283 --> 00:58:28,744
lf you had a shitty car,
you would've parked in the parking lot?

847
00:58:28,828 --> 00:58:31,706
lf l had a shitty car,
l might be a dead man.

848
00:58:31,789 --> 00:58:35,168
Somehow l think you're too lucky
for that.

849
00:58:35,209 --> 00:58:37,086
Thank you.

850
00:58:37,170 --> 00:58:39,964
Okay, 63, take three. Marker.

851
00:58:40,923 --> 00:58:43,342
Now.

852
00:58:43,426 --> 00:58:45,094
Action!

853
00:58:46,387 --> 00:58:50,683
No, goddamn it, you listen to me!
l've been around a while. l got a nose.

854
00:58:50,725 --> 00:58:54,520
This situation stinks.
lt stinks of the company.

855
00:58:54,562 --> 00:58:58,399
That's right, Peterson,
the fucking ClA. Ever heard of it?

856
00:58:58,483 --> 00:59:00,777
lt's the kind of operation--

857
00:59:00,860 --> 00:59:03,946
You don't understand what he's trying
to go for here.

858
00:59:04,030 --> 00:59:06,949
lt's hard to listen to your argument
when you don't understand.

859
00:59:07,033 --> 00:59:11,496
- Would you shut up, please?
- Kiss my ass!

860
00:59:11,537 --> 00:59:13,873
l have to cut.
My robe cut on the drawer.

861
00:59:13,956 --> 00:59:18,294
- For Christ's sakes!
- l like this guy. He's great.

862
00:59:18,377 --> 00:59:23,257
Waters?
Can l have some Volvic, please?

863
00:59:23,341 --> 00:59:25,343
Yeah, he's great.

864
00:59:26,761 --> 00:59:29,847
l heard the police came to see you
about this dead writer.

865
00:59:29,889 --> 00:59:33,559
- Who was this guy?
- His name was David Kahane.

866
00:59:33,643 --> 00:59:36,687
l never heard of him.
We ever hire him for anything?

867
00:59:36,729 --> 00:59:39,732
l was thinking about it.

868
00:59:39,774 --> 00:59:43,569
He pitched me a story.
l went there to talk to him about it.

869
00:59:43,611 --> 00:59:44,529
Jesus. Poor bastard. Just when his ship
comes in, some bastard blasts him--

870
00:59:44,570 --> 00:59:49,200
Jesus. Poor bastard. Just when his ship
comes in, some bastard blasts him--

871
00:59:49,283 --> 00:59:51,911
l don't want to criticize you...

872
00:59:51,953 --> 00:59:54,997
but l'm supposed to be talking
on the phone.

873
00:59:55,081 --> 00:59:56,916
Are the cops still bothering you?

874
00:59:56,999 --> 01:00:01,504
- No. No, l don't think so.
- Let Stuckel handle it.

875
01:00:01,587 --> 01:00:05,716
We'll give them passes to a screening.
They can sit behind Michelle Pfeiffer.

876
01:00:05,758 --> 01:00:07,969
They'll leave you alone.

877
01:00:09,262 --> 01:00:12,890
A guy named Joe Gillis called.

878
01:00:12,932 --> 01:00:17,603
He wants you to meet him at the
St. James Club at 10:00 on the patio.

879
01:00:17,687 --> 01:00:21,691
- Never heard of him.
- He said you'd know him.

880
01:00:21,774 --> 01:00:23,734
Anybody know who Joe Gillis is?

881
01:00:23,818 --> 01:00:26,529
He's a character William Holden played
in Sunset Boulevard.

882
01:00:26,612 --> 01:00:30,867
- The writer killed by a movie star.
- Gloria Swanson.

883
01:00:35,329 --> 01:00:39,083
Oh, that guy. Last week he said
he was Charles Foster Kane.

884
01:00:39,125 --> 01:00:41,961
A week before that
it was Rhett Butler.

885
01:00:42,003 --> 01:00:45,339
Why would they think l would kill
my own sister's husband?

886
01:00:47,133 --> 01:00:49,302
l was in love with him.

887
01:01:30,343 --> 01:01:35,097
- Griffin? Griffin.
- Malcolm McDowell, good to see you.

888
01:01:35,181 --> 01:01:38,726
Listen. The next time
you want to badmouth me...

889
01:01:38,810 --> 01:01:41,229
have the courage
to do it to my face.

890
01:01:41,312 --> 01:01:43,773
You guys are all the same.

891
01:01:54,117 --> 01:01:56,410
- You love it there?
- l love it. lt's wonderful.

892
01:01:56,494 --> 01:01:58,830
You love your career, don't you?
What is it?

893
01:01:58,913 --> 01:02:02,959
lt was a complete disaster.
Look what happened in Heaven's Gate.

894
01:02:03,042 --> 01:02:04,210
We both are concerned...

895
01:02:04,293 --> 01:02:06,629
about your career.

896
01:02:06,712 --> 01:02:09,382
Where l live, l know how people
think and feel.

897
01:02:10,550 --> 01:02:14,762
Montana will end you.
lt ended Cimino in Heaven's Gate.

898
01:02:14,846 --> 01:02:18,933
- Griffin Mill, hi. Andy Civella.
- Andy, how are you?

899
01:02:19,016 --> 01:02:22,687
l've got Andie MacDowell sitting over
here. You know her. She's so hot.

900
01:02:22,728 --> 01:02:25,022
- Come over and meet her.
- Still living in New York?

901
01:02:25,064 --> 01:02:28,067
l couldn't live here.
l'm allergic to happiness.

902
01:02:28,151 --> 01:02:32,071
Andie, it's good to see you again.
How are the kids?

903
01:02:32,155 --> 01:02:34,574
Great, thanks.
He's wonderful, thank you.

904
01:02:35,908 --> 01:02:38,286
You geniuses know each other.
Tom Oakley.

905
01:02:38,369 --> 01:02:41,414
- Yes, Hi, Tom.
- How are you?

906
01:02:41,497 --> 01:02:44,584
- Funny. l just saw Malcolm McDowell.
- Really?

907
01:02:44,667 --> 01:02:48,004
Roddy McDowall is related
to a cousin of my brother-in-law.

908
01:02:48,087 --> 01:02:50,756
Well, l'm not related
to either one of them.

909
01:03:00,766 --> 01:03:02,769
lf l write it, l direct it.

910
01:03:02,852 --> 01:03:06,272
The last three pictures you directed
were bombs!

911
01:03:06,355 --> 01:03:09,692
Thank you for the drink.
l've got to go.

912
01:03:09,776 --> 01:03:13,404
You've got to go?
We'll walk you to the car.

913
01:03:13,446 --> 01:03:15,907
No, it's okay.
Don't worry about it.

914
01:03:15,948 --> 01:03:18,493
We'd like to buy you a drink.

915
01:03:18,576 --> 01:03:21,537
l can't. l'm meeting someone.
Business.

916
01:03:21,621 --> 01:03:24,791
-We should tell him about Habeas Corpus.
-Of course, but he's a busy man.

917
01:03:24,874 --> 01:03:27,960
- ls there anyone waiting for me?
- No one's asked.

918
01:03:28,044 --> 01:03:31,714
l'm expecting someone.
l'll be out by the pool.

919
01:03:31,798 --> 01:03:34,717
But he'll get back to us.
Right, Griffin?

920
01:04:10,378 --> 01:04:11,796
Oh, sorry.

921
01:04:11,879 --> 01:04:14,549
- Jesus, Andy, it's you.
- Of course it's me.

922
01:04:14,632 --> 01:04:17,969
l can't ask you to join me.
l told you. l'm meeting somebody.

923
01:04:18,052 --> 01:04:20,888
Yeah. You're meeting me.
We got some big business.

924
01:04:20,972 --> 01:04:22,557
You? You?

925
01:04:22,640 --> 01:04:26,394
- Why not me?
- You think this is fucking funny?

926
01:04:26,477 --> 01:04:28,396
What are you talking about?

927
01:04:28,479 --> 01:04:33,109
Wouldn't she make a great Nora? l'd love
to write another Doll's House for her.

928
01:04:33,192 --> 01:04:35,945
Did you meet Tom Oakley?

929
01:04:36,028 --> 01:04:40,283
- Yes. You mean you didn't call me?
- No, l didn't call you.

930
01:04:40,366 --> 01:04:43,244
l'm sorry. l'm really sorry.

931
01:04:44,328 --> 01:04:47,748
Listen, l really am meeting somebody.

932
01:04:47,832 --> 01:04:51,377
There's no way l can hear a pitch
right now. Call me tomorrow.

933
01:04:51,461 --> 01:04:56,549
No, l can't do it tomorrow. l've got
a meeting at Paramount and Universal.

934
01:04:56,632 --> 01:04:58,259
Congratulations.

935
01:04:58,342 --> 01:05:00,678
- lf you don't hear it now, you'll lose.
- Then l lose it.

936
01:05:00,720 --> 01:05:02,889
lt'll take 20 seconds.
When your friend gets here--

937
01:05:02,972 --> 01:05:05,975
- What friend?
- Whoever you're gonna meet.

938
01:05:08,436 --> 01:05:10,396
Twenty-five words or less.

939
01:05:10,480 --> 01:05:14,233
Absolutely. You sit here, Tom.
Go.

940
01:05:15,318 --> 01:05:18,112
- The D.A. is at a moral crossroads.
- Tom! Jesus Christ.

941
01:05:19,864 --> 01:05:23,201
We open outside
the largest penitentiary in California.

942
01:05:23,242 --> 01:05:26,662
lt's night. lt's raining.
A limousine comes through the gate...

943
01:05:26,746 --> 01:05:30,166
past demonstrators holding
